What are meisner corpuscles and why are uncircumcised men preferred for any sexual clinical studies measuring pleasure?
Meissner’s corpuscles (also known as tactile corpuscles) are a type of mechanoreceptor located in the skin. They are specifically designed to be sensitive to light touch and low-frequency vibrations (around 10 to 50 Hz).
​Function and Anatomy
​These receptors are primarily found in "glabrous" (hairless) skin, such as the fingertips, palms, soles of the feet, and the lips. They are situated within the dermal papillae, which are the finger-like projections of the dermis that push up into the epidermis.
​When the skin is indented or touched lightly, the stack of flattened cells within the corpuscle is compressed, triggering a nerve impulse. Because they are rapidly adapting, they fire mostly when a touch begins or ends, making them excellent at detecting texture or something slipping through your fingers.
​Clinical Studies and the Prepuce (Foreskin)
​In the context of sexual health and pleasure studies, researchers often focus on uncircumcised men because of the unique concentration of Meissner’s corpuscles found in the prepuce (foreskin).
​The Ridged Band: This specific area of the prepuce is particularly dense with Meissner’s corpuscles. It is often cited as the most sensitive part of the penis to fine-touch stimuli.
​Baseline Sensitivity: Because circumcision removes the prepuce, it removes the ridged band and its high concentration of these receptors. Therefore, in studies measuring "peak" physiological sensitivity or the full range of tactile response in the male genitalia, uncircumcised men provide a data set that includes these specific specialized nerve endings.
​Keratinization: There is also a clinical hypothesis that the exposed glans of a circumcised penis may undergo "keratinization" (thickening of the skin), which might further alter sensitivity readings compared to the protected glans of an uncircumcised man.
​Researchers prefer this demographic when they need to map the maximum potential tactile sensitivity of the organ or when studying how different types of nerve endings contribute to the overall sensation of pleasure.